722099f-a.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 37th Street (East)
722099f-a.text:
Park Ave., west side, south from but not including East 40th to East
37th Streets, showing W.P.A. employees engaged in converting the former
railroad and afterward street car tunnel under Park Ave. for vehicular
use. The 4-story building (No. 86 Park Ave., at the N.W. corner of East
39th Street) prominently shown on the right.is the Princeton Club.
May 6, 1936.
W.P.A. Photo.
Federal Art Project.
CREDIT LINE IMPERATIVE ON ALL REPRODUCTIONS.

722066f-a.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 37th Street (East)
722066f-a.text:
Park Ave., at Nast 37th Street, showing the tablet erected by the
D.A.R. to Mary Lindley Murray. This marker is placed in the grass plot
that divides the traffic lanes of this thoroughfare.
September 8, 1937.
George D. Chinn.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.

722198f-a.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 37th Street
722198f-a.text:
45 Park Avenue, ''The Russell'', at S. E. corner of 37th Street, an
apartment hotel newly erected on the site of the old Judge Russell
residence.
In the foreground it will be noted that the center parks are being
altered slightly, for the first time since 1650 or earlier.
1923.
Joweph Smith, Photographer.
Gift of E.M. Jenks.
MAY Be REPRODUCED.

722067f.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 37th Street (East)
722067f.text:
Park Ave. (left), at the S.W. corner of East 37th Street, showing
the Union League Club. The club was organised in 1863 and most of its
members are politically of Republican proclivities. This is its fourth
building.
1936.
W.P.A. Photo.
Federal Writers Project.
CREDIT LINE IMPERATIVE ON ALL REPRODUCTIONS.

722068f-a.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 37th Street (East)
722068f-a.text:
Park Avenue, adjoining the N.E. corner of E. 37th
Street, showing at this location the garden establisned in
1913-16 by the Murray Hill Association to remedy the unsightly
appewrance of this vacant lot, the property of the I.R.T. Co.
In 1923 this will be included in the site for the 15 story
apartment house, No. bl Park Avenue.
Thru the center runs Park Avenue and to the left is E. 37th
Street, west of the Avenue. In 1931 the Union League Club House
will rise there. Opposite sare ann prominently shown is the
huilciug at the N.W. corner occupied by Charles Coster and which
has recently (N.Y. Sun June 14, 1939) becn sold for replacement
by an apartient house. This is to be of Georgian design and
harmonize with the Union League Club building.

722070f-a.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 37th Street
722070f-a.text:
Fark Avenue, east side, from 37th to 4lst Streets, but not showing
the small building on the N.E. corner of 41st Street.
No. 55 Park Avenue, in the right foreground, was built in 1923 on
the site of the old Interborough Garden shown in another picture.
From 38th to 39th Streets are shown the new apaI tment buildings
built between 1922 and 1924, and behind them the towers of the
Chanin and Chrysler Buildings. On the N.E. corner of 39th Street
the old houses are being demolished. The tall white building on
the N.E. corner of 40th Street is the architects' Building, erected
in 1916.
September 10, 1933.
P. L. Sperr, Photographer.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.

712388f-a.title: Manhattan: 37th Street (East) - Avenue L
712388f-a.text:
N. 37th Street, north side, west of Second Avenue. Adjoining
the corner is the Murray Hill Industrial High School. Adjacent to
same is the newly erected portion of the New York Telephone Co.
building. This replaced two former tenements, No's 229 and 231.
At Lexington Avenue appears the rear of the Hotel White. Note the
grade,giving this area its long fwmiliar name.
January 8, 1939
Somach Photo Service
New York City Tunnel Authority

722065f-a.text:
Park Avenue, at, adjoining and north of the N. W. corner
of East 37th Street. Prominently shown is the new apart-

April 26, 1940

722069f-a.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 37th Street (East)
722069f-a.text:
Park Avenue, west side, from E. 37th to 38th Streets,
as viewed northwestward from the east side of this thoroughfare
and showing in addition (left) the north side of 37th Street,
west froom Park to Madison Avenues.
The New York Times of June 14, 1939, reportsathe sale
for improvement of the corner property and the adjoining three
structures on 37th Street. Cromorising same are the Charles
Coster house (50 Pnrk Avenue), the former home of General Charles
P. Roe of the N. Y. S. N. G. (No. 35 E. 37th Street), the Cortlandt
F(e1d Bishop home (No. 33 E.) and the Issac W. How home (No. 31 E.).
The latter was sold by the estate nf William M. Savin and No's 33
and 35 by Miss Sarah Ahern.
At the extreme left of View 1 is the National Democratic
Club, located at the N. E. corner (Gf E. 37th Street and Madison
Avenue. View No. 2 is westward on 37th Street while No. 3 fs
southwestward to include the Union League Club (1931) at the S. W.
corner and opposite this new project.
Overhead appears the tower of the Empire State Building
and a cornice of the Engineering Combustion Building.
View 1: June 14, 1931
View 2: April 15, 1931
View 3: Sept. 9, 1933
